    <h2>Research Overview</h2>
    <p>
      This project examines whether environmental, social, and governance (ESG) mandates improve the 
      net financial performance of university endowment funds. Building on Aragon et al. (JFE 2025) 
      who document mixed performance effects of ESG integration, this research addresses a critical 
      gap: the absence of a systematic analysis of ESG implementation costs.
    </p>

    <div class="abstract">
      <strong>Abstract.</strong> 
      While Aragon et al. (JFE 2025) find mixed performance effects of ESG integration in university 
      endowments, their analysis does not systematically account for implementation costs — data acquisition, 
      specialist staffing, third-party ratings, and reporting. This project proposes a two-phase empirical 
      design: (1) a structured survey quantifying ESG expenditures across endowments, and (2) merging cost 
      data with performance data to construct a cost-effectiveness framework. The primary output is a 
      working paper offering evidence-based guidance for endowment fiduciaries.
    </div>

